That is an interesting observation. It points to a distinction between physical time and experienced time.

If experience only ever occurs in the present, then memory and imagination are ways the present can contain other times. When you remember your childhood, you aren’t traveling to the past—you’re having a present experience generated from stored traces. When you plan for tomorrow, you’re having a present experience of a possible future.

In that sense, thinking lets the present “hold” many temporal perspectives at once.

A nice way to phrase the idea is:

Consciousness never leaves the present. Thinking folds the past and future into it.

That also explains why humans can learn from history and prepare for events that haven’t happened yet. We can’t step outside the present, but we can bring representations of other times into it.

It’s a remarkable capability because it lets us act on causes and consequences that aren’t immediately in front of us. A squirrel mostly responds to the environment it perceives now. A human can plant an orchard they’ll never see mature, save for retirement decades away, or grieve someone who died years ago—all because the present can host those mental models.

There’s also an interesting flip side: if thinking is what populates the present with past and future, then attention becomes a kind of steering mechanism. You’re always in the same “now,” but you have some choice over which reconstructed world you’re inhabiting within it.

That doesn’t mean we can escape the present—it means the present is far richer than a single instant. It’s where perception, memory, imagination, and anticipation all meet. In that sense, the present isn’t just a point in time; it’s the stage on which your mind can reconstruct an entire lifetime.